<section class="section section--alt" id="qbo-adv-online-backup-restore-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What QuickBooks Online Advanced backup &amp; restore does.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Backup &amp; restore in QuickBooks Online Advanced is two linked things. The <em>backup</em> half runs on its own: your company data is captured automatically and continuously in the cloud, so there&rsquo;s a saved state of the file to fall back on without you having to remember to do anything. The <em>restore</em> half is the recovery: when something goes badly wrong, you can roll the company data back to an earlier point in time rather than trying to reverse the damage transaction by transaction.</p>
      <p>The case this is built for is a bulk mistake. An import that loaded thousands of wrong rows, a batch of transactions deleted in error, a mass change that hit the wrong list &mdash; the kind of damage that would take days to unwind by hand, if it could be unwound at all. Point-in-time restore is the lever for exactly those situations, and it&rsquo;s the protection the lower QuickBooks Online tiers don&rsquo;t include built in. That&rsquo;s a real reason the Advanced tier exists for some businesses.</p>
      <p>It&rsquo;s worth being precise about what this is and isn&rsquo;t. This is cloud restore for your <em>QuickBooks Online</em> data &mdash; it is not a QuickBooks <em>Desktop</em> <code>.QBB</code> file that you download and keep on your own machine. Those are different mechanisms that people often confuse because both use the word &ldquo;backup.&rdquo; And restore is broad by design: it rolls the file back, which means it can also undo good work done after the restore point. We describe how the feature actually behaves &mdash; we don&rsquo;t claim it covers things it doesn&rsquo;t, and we won&rsquo;t quote you Advanced-tier pricing here; that&rsquo;s Intuit&rsquo;s to set.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

